,Recommended,312360,29569869,Posted: 29 January,all,ronster1970,"Do not often contribute for reviews but thought I would say something about To End all Wars.I had been looking for sometime for a good WW1 strategy game.  I find most do not capture that deepth of the period.  They play more like a WW2 game with old looking units, using ""blitz"" tactics in a period when it would take weeks to move.TEAW captures that slower non mobile, entrenched feeling.  This game is not a repackaged WW2 clone.  In my current game I am playing the Western Entente, the Germans swept into Belgium and through Luxemburg, the french where pushed back (nearly to Paris!!) but then things just jammed up and litterly bogged down.  The French/Britsh forces have pushed the Germans back to the Ardenees, with a line of trenches going to Ypres in the north and all along the French Border in the south.  The fighting is slow and brutal, with a single German attack against dug in French lines costing over 120k troops!The feel of WW1 is there.  You cannot rush troops around nor do reckless quick attacks.  You must find soft spots and plan attacks or your troops will suffer the consequences.Diplomcy is interesting, have Japan and Portugual on my side and working on Italy.  Oddly the US seems to be swing toward the Central Entente, now that would be a problem if they joined germany.Technoogy is well managed, Gas attacks by the West (my side) where used in early spring 1915 and I am expecting retaliation by the Germans soon.The interface in clunky and needs work but once you figure it out it does become easier.  The map is amazing, really like the detail.Improvements could be the ability to search.  I am constantly trying to find units or generals and there is no real easy way to search, for example you cannot type in a name and find where it is.  Also, the command structure is confusing, but maybe command in this period is supposed to be confusing.Overall, really enjoy the game.  It will take you a few starts and restarts to really get a game going.  Recommend you print , read and have the manual next to you when you are playing, it helps alot as this game has a lot of depth to it.If you are looking for that WW1 game to fill the hole in your collections, I do recommend this one."
